    slug: "sahih-al-bukhari-complete",
    description: `Sahih Al-Bukhari is the most authoritative and revered collection of hadith in Islam, compiled by the great scholar Imam Muhammad ibn Ismail al-Bukhari (194–256 AH). This complete nine-volume set contains over seven thousand authentic narrations of the words, actions, and approvals of Prophet Muhammad (peace be upon him), meticulously verified through an unparalleled system of chain-of-narration scrutiny. Imam al-Bukhari spent sixteen years traveling across the Muslim world — from his native Bukhara through Makkah, Madinah, Kufah, Basrah, Egypt, and Syria — collecting approximately six hundred thousand narrations from which he selected only those that met his exacting criteria of authenticity. The result is a work that has been universally accepted by Muslim scholars for over twelve centuries as the most reliable book after the Quran itself.

The nine volumes are organized into ninety-seven books (kutub) and thousands of chapters (abwab), covering virtually every aspect of Islamic life. Volume one opens with the book of revelation (kitab al-wahy), documenting how the Quran was first revealed to the Prophet, followed by comprehensive sections on faith (iman), knowledge (ilm), purification (taharah), and prayer (salah). Subsequent volumes cover in exhaustive detail the topics of zakat, fasting, Hajj, trade and commerce, marriage and divorce, inheritance, Jihad, virtues of the Companions, medicine, food and drink, clothing and adornment, manners and etiquette, dreams and interpretations, and the description of the hereafter including paradise and hellfire. Each hadith is presented with its complete chain of narrators, allowing scholars to trace the transmission back to the original source, and Imam al-Bukhari frequently repeats key narrations under different chapter headings to highlight their relevance to multiple legal and theological points.

The scholarly methodology behind Sahih al-Bukhari sets it apart from all other hadith collections. Imam al-Bukhari imposed a condition that every narrator in a hadith chain must have met the next narrator in person, that each narrator must be known for their truthfulness, piety, and precision in memorization, and that the chain as a whole must be uninterrupted (muttasil) and free from any hidden defects (illah). He also required that each narrator's character be verified by multiple independent testimonies before accepting their narrations. This rigorous standard means that many hadith accepted by other compilers were rejected by Imam al-Bukhari, resulting in a collection of unmatched reliability. The work has been the subject of dozens of celebrated commentaries, including Fath al-Bari by Ibn Hajar al-Asqalani, which itself spans fifteen volumes and is considered one of the greatest achievements of Islamic scholarship. This complete nine-volume set is an essential reference for scholars, students of Islamic studies, imams, and any Muslim household seeking authentic knowledge of the Prophet's guidance.`,
