    slug: "sahih-muslim-complete",
    description: `Sahih Muslim is the second most authoritative collection of hadith in Islam, compiled by Imam Muslim ibn al-Hajjaj al-Qushayri (204–261 AH), a student of Imam al-Bukhari and one of the most meticulous scholars of hadith in Islamic history. This complete set contains approximately four thousand narrations (without repetition, and approximately seven thousand three hundred with repetition) organized with exceptional precision and a systematic categorization that has been praised by scholars for its logical flow and intellectual clarity. Imam Muslim spent over fifteen years traveling to collect narrations, visiting Kufah, the Hijaz, Egypt, and Syria, and gathering material from over two hundred and twenty teachers and sheikhs.

The hadith in Sahih Muslim are organized into approximately fifty-two books that systematically cover the major topics of Islamic law, theology, and practice. The collection begins with the book of faith (iman), detailing the pillars of Islamic belief and what constitutes true faith, followed by books on purification, prayer, zakat, fasting, Hajj, marriage, divorce, business transactions, jihad, governance, virtues of the Companions, asceticism, and descriptions of the Day of Judgment. Imam Muslim's method of arrangement is particularly noteworthy: rather than simply listing narrations under broad headings, he often groups related hadith together to present a comprehensive picture of a given topic, sometimes including multiple chains for the same narration to strengthen its authenticity and sometimes placing different narrations side by side to show the various angles from which the Companions understood the Prophet's teachings.

The authentication methodology of Imam Muslim is regarded as the most rigorous after (or in some scholarly opinions, equal to) that of Imam al-Bukhari. While Imam al-Bukhari required that narrators meet face-to-face, Imam Muslim accepted narrations where a narrator simply lived in the same city as their teacher, provided other conditions of reliability were met. However, Imam Muslim imposed stricter conditions in other areas: he was more particular about avoiding repetition and more careful about presenting narrations with their complete chains. The result is a collection that scholars describe as having the most perfectly organized structure among all hadith works. The text has been illuminated by numerous celebrated commentaries, most notably the multi-volume commentary by Imam al-Nawawi, which remains one of the most widely studied works of hadith exegesis. This complete set of Sahih Muslim is indispensable for students of Islamic knowledge, researchers, and anyone who seeks an authentic and well-organized record of the Prophet's sunnah.`,
