    slug: "tafseer-ibn-kathir-complete",
    description: `Tafseer Ibn Kathir is one of the most celebrated and widely studied exegeses of the Holy Quran in the entire history of Islamic scholarship. Compiled by the renowned scholar Hafiz Imad al-Din Ismail ibn Kathir (701–774 AH), this complete ten-volume set represents a monumental work of Quranic interpretation that draws primarily upon the Quran itself, the authentic hadith of Prophet Muhammad (peace be upon him), and the statements of the Companions and early successors (tabi'un). The methodology of Tafseer Ibn Kathir follows the foundational principle that the best interpretation of the Quran is through the Quran — meaning that verses are first understood in light of other related Quranic passages — followed by interpretation through the Sunnah, and then through the understanding of those who witnessed the revelation firsthand.

Each volume of this ten-volume set covers specific surahs of the Quran in order, beginning with Surah al-Fatihah and proceeding through to Surah an-Nas. For every verse or passage, Ibn Kathir provides the following layers of explanation: first, he identifies the context of revelation (asbab al-nuzul) where applicable, explaining the historical circumstances that led to a particular verse being revealed. Second, he presents the relevant hadith narrations that explain or elaborate upon the verse, carefully noting the authenticity of each narration. Third, he provides the opinions of the Companions such as Ibn Abbas, Ubayy ibn Kab, and Abdullah ibn Masud, as well as the views of the major tabi'un including Mujahid, Qatadah, and Hasan al-Basri. Fourth, he addresses linguistic and rhetorical aspects of the Arabic text, drawing upon classical Arabic grammar and philology to clarify difficult constructions or unusual vocabulary. Fifth, he discusses any legal rulings (ahkam) derived from the verse, connecting the tafsir to the practical application of Islamic law.

The work is particularly valued for its detailed coverage of Quranic stories, including extensive narratives about the prophets (Adam, Nuh, Ibrahim, Musa, Isa, and others), the events surrounding the Prophet Muhammad's life, and the histories of past nations mentioned in the Quran such as the people of Ad, Thamud, and Madyan. Ibn Kathir also pays careful attention to theological issues, providing clear explanations of verses related to the attributes of Allah, the Day of Judgment, predestination, and the nature of faith. His treatment of these topics consistently reflects the orthodox Sunni position and carefully avoids the philosophical speculations and allegorical interpretations that characterize some other works of tafsir. This ten-volume set is regarded as an essential reference in every Islamic library, a staple of madrasah curricula worldwide, and a resource that no serious student of the Quran should be without.`,
