    slug: "ihya-ulum-al-din",
    description: `Ihya Ulum al-Din, meaning "The Revival of the Religious Sciences," is one of the most influential and widely read works in the history of Islamic literature. Written by the great scholar, theologian, and mystic Abu Hamid Muhammad al-Ghazali (450–505 AH), this encyclopedic work addresses the entire spectrum of Islamic practice and spirituality, covering both the outward acts of worship and the inward states of the heart. Al-Ghazali composed this masterpiece during a period of spiritual crisis and renewal, after he had already achieved the highest academic honors as a professor at the Nizamiyyah madrasah in Baghdad, and it represents the synthesis of his vast learning in Islamic law, theology, philosophy, and Sufism into a unified guide for the spiritual development of the individual Muslim.

The work is divided into four major parts (quarters), each containing ten books, for a total of forty books. The first quarter, titled "Acts of Worship" (ibadat), covers the foundational pillars of Islamic practice — purification, prayer, zakat, fasting, pilgrimage, recitation of the Quran, dhikr, supplication (dua), and the Friday and congregational prayers — but with a unique emphasis on the inner spiritual dimensions and the hidden faults (awrat) that can undermine these acts. Al-Ghazali explains, for example, that while the outward form of prayer may be technically correct, it becomes empty if the heart is distracted, if one prays merely to be seen by others, or if one fails to achieve the state of humility (khushu) that is the true essence of the prayer. The second quarter, "Worldly Usages" (adat), addresses the everyday matters of life — eating, marriage, earning a livelihood, friendship, travel, and the permissibility and prohibition of various activities — showing how these mundane aspects of life can be transformed into acts of worship when performed with the correct intention and within the boundaries of Islamic law.

The third quarter, "Destructive Vices" (muhlikat), is a penetrating analysis of the spiritual diseases that afflict the human heart, including the love of this world, anger, envy, hatred, riyaa (showing off in worship), miserliness, love of status, arrogance, and conceit. For each vice, al-Ghazali provides a thorough diagnosis of its causes, a description of its symptoms and consequences, and a detailed prescription for its cure. The fourth quarter, "Saving Virtues" (munjiyat), describes the praiseworthy qualities that the Muslim must cultivate — repentance (tawbah), patience (sabr), gratitude (shukr), fear and hope, poverty and asceticism, tawakkul (reliance upon Allah), love of Allah and the Prophet, sincerity (ikhlas), and self-examination (muhasabah). The work has been summarized, commented upon, and translated into dozens of languages, and its influence extends far beyond the Islamic world. This complete set is essential reading for anyone interested in Islamic spirituality, ethics, and the reform of the soul.`,
    metaDescription: "Ihya Ulum al-Din by Imam al-Ghazali is a 40-book masterwork on Islamic spirituality. Covers worship, ethics, vices, and virtues of the heart."
