    slug: "kitab-at-tawheed",
    description: `Kitab at-Tawheed, meaning "The Book of Monotheism," is one of the most important and foundational works on Islamic theology and creed (aqeedah) ever written. Authored by the renowned scholar Shaykh Muhammad ibn Abdul Wahhab (1703–1792), this book provides a systematic and comprehensive exposition of the Islamic concept of tawheed — the absolute oneness and uniqueness of Allah — and its various categories, along with a detailed analysis of shirk (associating partners with Allah) in all its forms. The book is structured as a series of chapters, each addressing a specific aspect of tawheed or a particular manifestation of shirk, supported extensively by evidence from the Quran and the authentic hadith of Prophet Muhammad (peace be upon him).

The book begins by establishing the fundamental obligation of tawheed as the primary purpose of human creation, citing the Quranic verse "And I created not the jinn and mankind except that they should worship Me" (Surah adh-Dhariyat: 56). It then categorizes tawheed into its three recognized dimensions: Tawheed ar-Rububiyyah (the oneness of Allah's lordship — acknowledging that Allah alone is the Creator, Sustainer, and Controller of all things), Tawheed al-Uluhiyyah or Tawheed al-Ibadah (the oneness of worship — directing all acts of worship exclusively to Allah), and Tawheed al-Asma was-Sifat (the oneness of Allah's names and attributes — affirming for Allah the beautiful names and perfect attributes that He has described Himself with, without distortion, denial, or comparison to creation). Each category is explored with extensive Quranic evidence and prophetic narrations.

A significant portion of the book is devoted to identifying and warning against the various forms of shirk that can undermine a Muslim's faith. The author discusses major shirk (associating partners with Allah in His lordship or worship), minor shirk (such as riyyaa or showing off in worship, and swearing by other than Allah), and the practical forms that shirk can take in daily life, including seeking intercession from the dead, making vows to other than Allah, wearing amulets and charms for protection instead of relying upon Allah, and sacrificing in the name of other than Allah. The book also covers related topics including the pillars of Islam, the conditions of the testimony of faith, the meaning of la ilaha illa Allah, the virtues of tawheed and the grave consequences of shirk. Kitab at-Tawheed has been studied, taught, and commented upon extensively across the Muslim world for over two centuries, and it remains one of the most widely used textbooks for teaching correct Islamic belief in mosques, madrasahs, and Islamic educational institutions at every level.`,
    metaDescription: "Kitab at-Tawheed by Shaykh ibn Abdul Wahhab explains Islamic monotheism and warns against shirk. Covers tawheed categories with Quran and hadith evidence."
