    slug: "majmu-al-fatawa-selected",
    description: `Majmu al-Fatawa is a monumental collection of Islamic legal opinions (fatawa) issued by the great scholar Shaykh al-Islam Imam Taqi al-Din Ahmad ibn Taymiyyah (661–728 AH), one of the most prolific and influential Islamic scholars in history. This selected volumes set brings together the most important and frequently referenced legal opinions from the complete collection, which in its full form spans dozens of volumes and covers virtually every aspect of Islamic jurisprudence, theology, and practice. The fatawa of Ibn Taymiyyah are distinguished by their rigorous methodology, their reliance upon the primary sources of Islamic law — the Quran, the authentic Sunnah, the consensus of the Companions, and sound analogy — and their willingness to challenge established scholarly opinions when the evidence demands it.

The collection addresses an extraordinarily wide range of topics. In the field of aqeedah ( creed), Ibn Taymiyyah's fatawa provide detailed explanations of the names and attributes of Allah, the nature of faith (iman), the correct understanding of tawheed, the status of those who commit major sins, and responses to the theological positions of various philosophical and sectarian groups. In the field of fiqh (jurisprudence), the fatawa cover prayer, fasting, zakat, Hajj, marriage, divorce, business transactions, inheritance, criminal law, and jihad with remarkable depth and practical detail. Ibn Taymiyyah was particularly known for his independent juristic reasoning — while he was trained in the Hanbali school, he frequently issued rulings that differed from the established positions of all four madhahib when he found stronger evidence in the primary sources.

The selected volumes in this set include some of the most famous and influential fatawa ever written. Among the most significant are the lengthy fatwa on the principles of Islamic jurisprudence (usul al-fiqh), which provides a masterful overview of how Islamic legal rulings are derived; the fatwa on divorce pronouncements made under duress or in a state of anger; the fatwa on the permissibility of various modern financial transactions; and the extensive theological fatwa that defend the orthodox Sunni position on the attributes of Allah against both extreme rationalists and extreme literalists. The collection also includes responses to questions about Sufi practices, the status of visiting graves, the use of intermediaries in supplication, and the boundaries between permissible cultural practices and religious innovations (bidah). Each fatwa typically begins with the question posed to Ibn Taymiyyah, followed by a detailed response that cites the relevant Quranic verses, hadith narrations, statements of the Companions, and precedents from earlier scholars. This selected set is an invaluable resource for scholars, students of Islamic law, and anyone who seeks to understand the reasoning behind Islamic legal positions on complex contemporary issues.`,
